    "lesson_id": "011",
    "trigger_word": "estis",
    "title": "LESSON 11: PAST TENSE",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "To talk about the past in Esperanto, change",
          "the verb ending from -as to -is. That's it!",
          "",
          "PRESENT      →  PAST:",
          "mi estas     →  mi estis   (I am → I was)",
          "vi parolas   →  vi parolis (you speak → spoke)",
          "li manĝas    →  li manĝis  (he eats → he ate)",
          "",
          "The ending -is works for ALL subjects:",
          "mi estis     =  I was",
          "vi estis     =  you were",
          "li estis     =  he was",
          "ni estis     =  we were",
          "ili estis    =  they were",
          "",
          "One form for everyone. No irregular verbs!",
          "Just replace -as with -is and you're done."
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dek unu"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "012",
    "trigger_word": "estos",
    "title": "LESSON 12: FUTURE TENSE",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "For future tense, change the verb ending",
          "to -os. Simple as that!",
          "",
          "PRESENT      →  FUTURE:",
          "mi estas     →  mi estos   (I am → will be)",
          "vi parolas   →  vi parolos (speak → will speak)",
          "li manĝas    →  li manĝos  (he eats → will eat)",
          "",
          "ALL THREE TENSES TOGETHER:",
          "mi parolis   =  I spoke     (past -is)",
          "mi parolas   =  I speak     (present -as)",
          "mi parolos   =  I will speak (future -os)",
          "",
          "Three tenses, three endings. Always the",
          "same for all subjects. Esperanto makes",
          "verb conjugation beautifully simple!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dek du"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "013",
    "trigger_word": "pomo",
    "title": "LESSON 13: ACCUSATIVE -N (OBJECT)",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The accusative -n marks the DIRECT OBJECT -",
          "the thing that receives the action.",
          "",
          "DIRECT OBJECT = receives the action:",
          "",
          "La kato vidas la hundon.",
          "(The cat sees the dog.)",
          "",
          "kato   = subject (who sees)",
          "hundon = object (who is seen) + -n",
          "",
          "MORE EXAMPLES:",
          "Mi manĝas pomon.  = I eat an apple.",
          "Mi legas libron.  = I read a book.",
          "Ŝi amas muzikon.  = She loves music.",
          "",
          "The -n marks what receives the action.",
          "Without -n? It's the subject doing it!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dek tri"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "014",
    "trigger_word": "glaso",
    "title": "LESSON 14: -N FOR DIRECTION",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The -n ending also shows DIRECTION toward",
          "a place. This is its second major use!",
          "",
          "LOCATION vs DIRECTION:",
          "Mi estas en la domo.  = I am in the house.",
          "Mi iras en la domon.  = I go into the house.",
          "",
          "La akvo estas en la glaso.",
          "(The water is in the glass.)",
          "Mi verŝas akvon en la glason.",
          "(I pour water into the glass.)",
          "",
          "MORE EXAMPLES:",
          "Mi iras hejmen.      = I go home(ward).",
          "Ni iras Londonon.    = We're going to London.",
          "",
          "The -n shows movement TOWARD something.",
          "No -n? You're already there!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dek kvar"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "015",
    "trigger_word": "voli",
    "title": "LESSON 15: MODAL VERBS",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "Modal verbs express ability, desire, or",
          "obligation. The main verb stays in the",
          "infinitive form (ending in -i).",
          "",
          "THE THREE KEY MODALS:",
          "povi  = can, to be able to",
          "voli  = to want to",
          "devi  = must, to have to",
          "",
          "EXAMPLES:",
          "Mi povas paroli.     = I can speak.",
          "Mi volas manĝi.      = I want to eat.",
          "Ni devas lerni.      = We must learn.",
          "",
          "STRUCTURE: modal + infinitive",
          "Li povas veni morgaŭ. = He can come tomorrow.",
          "",
          "The infinitive never changes!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dek kvin"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "016",
    "trigger_word": "mia",
    "title": "LESSON 16: POSSESSIVE PRONOUNS",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "Possessive pronouns show ownership. Add -a",
          "to any personal pronoun to make it possessive.",
          "",
          "THE POSSESSIVES:",
          "",
          "  mi  → mia    = I → my",
          "  vi  → via    = you → your",
          "  li  → lia    = he → his",
          "  ŝi  → ŝia    = she → her",
          "  ĝi  → ĝia    = it → its",
          "  ni  → nia    = we → our",
          "  ili → ilia   = they → their",
          "",
          "EXAMPLES:",
          "Mia domo estas granda. = My house is big.",
          "Kie estas via libro?   = Where is your book?",
          "Ŝia amiko venis.       = Her friend came.",
          "",
          "Like adjectives, add -j for plural nouns:",
          "miaj libroj = my books"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dek ses"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "017",
    "trigger_word": "mem",
    "title": "LESSON 17: REFLEXIVE PRONOUNS",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "Reflexive pronouns refer back to the subject.",
          "Esperanto uses SI for third person reflexives.",
          "",
          "SI, SIN, SIA:",
          "si   = himself/herself/itself/themselves",
          "sin  = (accusative) oneself",
          "sia  = his/her/its/their own",
          "",
          "EXAMPLES:",
          "Li lavas sin.     = He washes himself.",
          "Ŝi vidas sin.     = She sees herself.",
          "Ili helpas sin.   = They help themselves.",
          "",
          "SIA vs LIA/ŜIA:",
          "Li amas sian hundon.",
          "→ He loves his dog. (his own)",
          "Li amas lian hundon.",
          "→ He loves his dog. (someone else's)"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dek sep"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "018",
    "trigger_word": "kun",
    "title": "LESSON 18: PREPOSITIONS",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 2,
        "content": [
          "Prepositions show relationships between words.",
          "They NEVER change form in Esperanto!",
          "",
          "LOCATION & DIRECTION:",
          "en   = in, inside      sur  = on, upon",
          "sub  = under           super = above, over",
          "apud = beside, next to inter = between",
          "ĉe   = at, by          ĉirkaŭ = around",
          "",
          "EXAMPLES:",
          "La kato estas sub la tablo.",
          "(The cat is under the table.)",
          "",
          "Mi sidas apud vi.",
          "(I sit beside you.)",
          "",
          "Remember: add -n to the noun after a",
          "preposition ONLY to show direction/motion."
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dek ok"
      },
      {
        "page": 2,
        "total_pages": 2,
        "content": [
          "MORE ESSENTIAL PREPOSITIONS:",
          "",
          "al   = to, toward      de   = from, of",
          "kun  = with            sen  = without",
          "por  = for (purpose)   pri  = about",
          "per  = by means of     tra  = through",
          "ĝis  = until, up to    krom = except, besides",
          "",
          "EXAMPLES:",
          "Mi iras al la parko.   = I go to the park.",
          "Libro de mia amiko.    = A book of my friend.",
          "Ni parolas pri vi.     = We talk about you.",
          "Ŝi venis kun frato.    = She came with brother.",
          "",
          "TIP: Most prepositions work like English,",
          "but JE is a wildcard for unclear relations!",
          "Je la tria horo. = At three o'clock."
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
]
